I am practicing asana with these series of videos for the second time. Since the first time, several years ago, the gift of time and experience has brought me wisdom to "find what feels good" despite what Adriene is instructing in the video. For example, I listened to my body and knew that I wanted to modify the poses. Instead of downward facing dog, I chose extended childs' pose and to be on hands and knees, then a modified warrior in a lower to the ground position. I used my blocks. I chose to do what my body was calling for using the knowledge of yoga I have learned from Adriene and from other teachers over the years. Above all else, I was kind to myself. I believe that's what Adriene would want. I will continue on this path of choosing self-care and not forcing my body into shapes; I am a creator being with unlimited potential (and so are you), and I have the freedom to choose what I want and need to do for and with my body. To anyone who reads this, I hope you take a moment to recognize how beautiful, magical, and miraculous YOU ARE. You are enough.

Always had weak lower back issues. Supposedly I have a herniated disc and degenerative disc disease. Duh who doesn't. It's taken a few months not one or two weeks. But it's as if my body is bulletproofing itself and functioning as it was intended rather than my dumb ass pushing through. For years it took my breath to tie my steel toes. I've been sitting in a squat this entire text. Hahaha..Do it every day. If you miss don't miss twice.. know a huge reward will unfold only for those who know the importance of making time. To many of us watching we've lived half our lives already. I encourage anyone over 40 to get with it. Workout like our lives depend on it. It does.

Day 5: Yoga with Adriene - Feel Alive Flow. A long day, a lengthening day. Yet, I came to the end of the session saying to myself, "Wait, it's over already?" This session is dominated by breathing and stretching through the sides of our bodies. I found myself coming to this session filled with the distractions and worries of my every day life, and had to start over through the first set of poses in order to bring my focus to my mat. I struggled again to keep my breathing relaxed and in line with my poses, however, by simply keeping my focus on it and trying, I found myself moving through the poses. This session built and built upon itself until I suddenly found myself at the end poses. It was a wonderful way to break from the momentum of my daily life and bring myself back to myself. Thank you once again Adriene for a wonderful session. Namaste.

How does it feel to be alive today, you ask? Well, at the start of 2021 being alive feels lonely, it feels repetitive and difficult. That doesn't mean, however, that I'm not grateful to be alive. Every day, one of the first things I do when I wake up is thank the universe for giving me a new day. Even in the times we're living and even when simple things like getting out of bed seem incredibly hard, there's a million things to be grateful for. Today, I choose to focus on the things I'm thankful for: my body for allowing me to do yoga, Adriene for being such a sweet and loving teacher, and the community we've built here for always giving me the motivation to keep showing up to the mat. If anyone is reading this in 2021, I wish you find the strength to keep moving through the hard times and I hope you find gratefulness in every breath. Treat yourself kindly. Sending you love and light. xx

I started this challenge because I moved to South America for my husband's job. We lived in NYC prior and didn't feel right owning a pet in our cramped space, so with my free time we decided to rescue two dogs. Taking care of our girls and being a homemaker is very exhausting. I spent every day of 2017 in the gym lifting weights, but being here, I haven't had the energy (we're in the Andes and the elevation is practically suffocating!) Culture shock hit me pretty hard, something I wasn't expecting, on top of the breathing problems and just general anxiety from not being able to properly express myself in a new language, I started feeling pretty depressed. I decided 6 months of laziness was far too much and found this series. It took me a week and a half to finally hit day 5 (mostly due to constant travel, but also some laziness). I'm definitely doing it at my own pace, but it's also motivated me to get back in the gym. It's also the perfect remedy after a day of lifting because the stretches are sooooo delicious! Thank you Adriene for reminding me to be alive in every moment and really appreciate my life.
